    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Feline Asthma?</h2>
      <p>Feline asthma is a chronic inflammatory condition of the lower airways, triggered by allergens or irritants. The airways become inflamed, narrowed, and hypersensitive — causing episodes of coughing, wheezing, and laboured breathing. It is one of the most common respiratory conditions in cats, affecting an estimated 1–5% of the population.</p>
      <p>Artie had asthma alongside FIV, hyperthyroidism, and the neurological symptoms that ultimately ended his life. Managing his asthma was complicated by the interaction with his other conditions — anti-inflammatory medications can affect immune function in FIV-positive cats, and the relationship between respiratory distress and neurological decline was difficult to untangle.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="signs" class="content-section">
      <h2>Signs to Watch For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Coughing — often mistaken for hairball attempts. A cat with asthma typically crouches low, extends the neck, and has a dry, hacking cough without producing a hairball.</li>
        <li>Wheezing or noisy breathing</li>
        <li>Open-mouth breathing (in cats, this is always worth investigating — it is not normal)</li>
        <li>Laboured or rapid breathing at rest</li>
        <li>Blue-tinged gums (cyanosis) — a medical emergency</li>
        <li>Exercise intolerance, increased lethargy</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Open-mouth breathing or blue gums in a cat is a medical emergency.</strong> Do not wait. Go to an emergency vet immediately.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnosis" class="content-section">
      <h2>Diagnosis</h2>
      <p>Feline asthma is typically diagnosed through a combination of clinical signs, chest X-rays (which may show a characteristic "donut" pattern or air trapping), and response to treatment. Bronchoscopy can provide a definitive diagnosis but is more invasive and usually reserved for difficult cases.</p>
      <p>It's important to rule out other causes of respiratory distress — heart disease, pleural effusion, pneumonia, and lung tumours can all look similar to asthma on presentation. Don't accept an asthma diagnosis without appropriate imaging.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="treatment" class="content-section">
      <h2>Treatment and Management</h2>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Corticosteroids</div>
          <div class="med-desc">The primary treatment for feline asthma. Reduce airway inflammation. Can be given as injectable, oral (prednisolone), or inhaled. Inhaled steroids (via a spacer device like the AeroKat) deliver medication directly to the lungs with fewer systemic side effects — preferred for long-term management. Important consideration in cats with diabetes or FIV, where systemic steroids carry additional risks.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Bronchodilators</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Open the airways during an acute episode. Albuterol (salbutamol) via inhaler is the most common rescue medication. Works within minutes. Every asthmatic cat household should have a bronchodilator on hand for emergencies. Can be given through the same AeroKat spacer as inhaled steroids.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Trigger management</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Identifying and removing triggers is as important as medication. Common triggers: scented candles, air fresheners, dusty cat litter, cigarette smoke, cleaning products, and perfume. Switching to a low-dust, unscented litter alone sometimes produces significant improvement.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>US and Canada note:</strong> The AeroKat feline inhaler spacer is available in the US and Canada and works with standard human inhalers (albuterol, fluticasone). Ask your vet about training your cat to accept the mask — most cats adapt within a few weeks, and it makes ongoing management much easier than oral medication.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="overlapping" class="content-section">
      <h2>When Asthma Overlaps with Other Conditions</h2>
      <p>Asthma rarely travels alone in senior cats. The overlap with heart disease deserves particular attention — both can cause breathing difficulty and coughing, but the treatment is very different. Steroids that help asthma can worsen heart failure. Diuretics that help heart failure have no effect on asthma.</p>
      <p>Before starting steroids for presumed asthma, ask whether heart disease has been ruled out. A cardiac ultrasound (echocardiogram) is the definitive test.</p>
      <p>In FIV-positive cats like Artie, long-term systemic steroids require careful consideration — they further suppress an already compromised immune system. Inhaled steroids are strongly preferred in this situation.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Has heart disease been ruled out as a cause of the breathing difficulty?</li>
        <li>Can we use inhaled steroids instead of oral, to reduce systemic effects?</li>
        <li>Should I have a bronchodilator at home for acute episodes? Can you show me how to use it?</li>
        <li>What are the triggers most likely to affect my cat, and how do we identify them?</li>
        <li>Given my cat's other conditions, are there any steroid risks I need to monitor for?</li>
        <li>What signs indicate this is becoming an emergency rather than a routine episode?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

